<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="53774884" data-username="sonofsysiphus" data-role="username">A. Hairyhanded Gent</a></span>






<span><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1633260837" class="parent-link" data-role="parent-link"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-forward" title="in reply to"></i> YourSupremeCommander</a></span>

</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1633285809" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Monday, October 13, 2014 4:09 PM">4 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>For god's sake, everyone knows that. It's not hypocrisy, it's simply trying to oppose any expansion of power, in any way possible. In this case it's taking the rhetorical high ground.</p><p>And, of course, China will ignore it, and life will go on as usual.</p><p>This is real politik, my good man...</p>

</div>

