<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="80372319" data-username="zachary_klein" data-role="username">Zachary Klein</a></span>






<span><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1634496953" class="parent-link" data-role="parent-link"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-forward" title="in reply to"></i> Be Way</a></span>

</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1634783442" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Tuesday, October 14, 2014 1:11 PM">3 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>It's called the Law of the Sea Convention, and pretty much every country on earth subscribes to the same interpretation of the law--except for China.  They want complete military dominion over the Exclusive Economic Zone (200 nautical miles from shore), which is something no one else agrees with.  So please, don't speak for "Asians."</p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
