<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="80372319" data-username="zachary_klein" data-role="username">Zachary Klein</a></span>






<span><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1638270040" class="parent-link" data-role="parent-link"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-forward" title="in reply to"></i> Bulos Qoqish</a></span>

</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1638411060" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Thursday, October 16, 2014 5:22 AM">a day ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>Yes, that same Law of the Sea Convention.  The one that the U.S. Navy still adheres to in spite of Congress's unwillingness to ratify.  And let's not forget America's adherence to the San Remo Manual and the Hague Convention of 1907, the latter of which China violates to a dangerous degree with its development of offensive sea mines.  Say what you will about American ground operations, but in terms of our naval policy, we do more to uphold international norms than any other nation.  China is so far outside of the international consensus it's not even funny.</p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
