<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1635051859" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Tuesday, October 14, 2014 4:40 PM">3 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>Of course, there's one crucial difference between the Soviet Union's millitary buildup and China's- Deng pegged the military buildup to GDP, insisting that the  military's share could never rise about 4% on his watch (unlike the Soviet Union, whose military took roughly 25-35% at it's peak).</p><p>It never has, but back when 4% meant 4% of squat, it wasn't much of a threat. Now that it's 4% of the world's second largest economy... that's a whole different ballgame.</p><p>Smart. Very, very smart.</p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
