<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="60732716" data-username="GiantTribble" data-role="username">Myra Esoteric</a></span>






<span><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1635058429" class="parent-link" data-role="parent-link"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-forward" title="in reply to"></i> Hanfeizi</a></span>

</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1635156544" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Tuesday, October 14, 2014 5:50 PM">3 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>There are already independent countries with a similar cultural background to Tibet and Xin Jiang such as Bhutan and Uzbekistan.</p><p>Look I don't give a damn if they become independent but I just think a lot of pro-West commentators use 'free Tibet' as an excuse to screw with countries that aren't soft colonies of the US.</p><p>The vast majority of people in China, regardless of area, honestly don't give a damn. But from what I know about these areas like Tibet, that are economically depressed and net tax recipients, is that many residents have good reason to want to remain as part of China economically.</p><p>BTW. Only Inner Mongolia is politically part of China, the other parts are more influenced by Russia.</p>

</div>

