</div>


<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="100227345" data-username="hanfeizi" data-role="username">Hanfeizi</a></span>






<span><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1633768246" class="parent-link" data-role="parent-link"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-forward" title="in reply to"></i> Riley 1066</a></span>

</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1635064752" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Tuesday, October 14, 2014 4:49 PM">3 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>They have as legitimate a claim as anyone else.</p><p>In the eyes of international law, the Qing dynasty was the legitimate claimant to Tibet. The Republic of China was the successor state of the Qing Empire, and still claims ownership of Tibet. In the 1970s and 80s, international bodies gradually recognized the PRC as having replaced the ROC as successor state.</p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
</div>
</div>
