<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="56461872" data-username="disqus_hbolPDDKPS" data-role="username">Roger Thornhill</a></span>






<span><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1633330182" class="parent-link" data-role="parent-link"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-forward" title="in reply to"></i> NicolasBourbaki</a></span>

</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1633400667" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Monday, October 13, 2014 5:31 PM">4 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev, himself a Ukrainian, "gave" Crimea to Ukraine in 1954, when all of the republics were under the umbrella of the USSR. It was not the 1970s. Before that, Crimea was regarded as Russia, particularly since so much Russian blood had been spilt there.</p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
</div>
</div>
