<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="65460851" data-username="duncantweedy" data-role="username">Duncan Tweedy</a></span>






</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1633466082" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Monday, October 13, 2014 6:08 PM">4 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>This might be one of the more important articles written this year.  This topic has needed a high profile in-depth survey of events for some time now.  Howard W. French and The Atlantic are to be commended.</p><p></p><blockquote>a Filipino...former admiral and national-security adviser...[asked] “Do you think it is natural for a superpower to behave the way China is?”</blockquote><p></p><p>China's lack of diplomacy and soft power will prove to be its greatest weakness in any global contest of influence.    </p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
