<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="22201231" data-username="Garaboncias" data-role="username">Sisyphus</a></span>






<span><a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1635870776" class="parent-link" data-role="parent-link"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-forward" title="in reply to"></i> SgtKonus</a></span>

</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1635919600" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Wednesday, October 15, 2014 12:40 AM">3 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>Actually, the Chinese had quite a few of those, too, and not a few of them lead armies, or naval squadrons, very successfully. It was the court eunuchs who ran China pretty much up until the turn of the 20th century - or the last Emperor - when the practice was discontinued. Eunuchs in the employ of the Sultans were mostly employed as harem guards, while in China they wielded actual, real power; administrative as well as military.</p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
</div>
</div>
