<div class="post-body">
<header>
<span class="post-byline">

<span class="author publisher-anchor-color"><a href="#" data-action="profile" data-user="33551877" data-username="Lordhalston" data-role="username">Lordhalston</a></span>






</span>

<span class="post-meta">
<span class="bullet time-ago-bullet" aria-hidden="true">•</span>


<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/11/chinas-dangerous-game/380789/#comment-1635666289" data-role="relative-time" class="time-ago" title="Tuesday, October 14, 2014 9:54 PM">3 days ago</a>

</span>


</header>


<div class="post-body-inner">

<div class="post-message-container" data-role="message-container">

<div class="publisher-anchor-color" data-role="message-content">
<div class="post-message " data-role="message" dir="auto">

<p>Great Article however, the author never discussed "soft power" and the cultural relationship that Japan and the United States share with each<br>other. Americans (those who know the difference between China and Japan)<br>overwhelmingly despise China and have multiple cultural ties to Japanese<br>culture. The true and final question is: Are Americans willing to die for<br>Tokyo? Beijing thinks not but, I’m willing to wager that Beijing is wrong. The<br>next few Aircraft carriers we decommission should be gifted to Japan. The President<br>should visit the Yaukuni Shrine along with the UK and Australian Prime Ministers.<br>There is no reason why China, a morally bankrupt oppressive dictatorship should<br>be anything besides a pariah in the eyes of the international community. The<br>Dalai Lama still cannot return home, Tibet is not free, Hong Kong is oppressed,<br>and the South China sea is not for sale.</p>

</div>

<span class="post-media"><ul data-role="post-media-list"></ul></span>
